data.name: label6.Text
data.value:
G is used to ENCODE the message 'm' into codewords <U>. G = [ P | I ]
H is used to DECODE the received vector back to the original codeword <U>. H = [ I | P' ]
G = Generator Matrix. P = Parity Matrix. H = Parity Check. I = Identity Matrix. ' = Transpose.

data.name: label5.Text
data.value: The recieved vector <r> is a valid codeword, iff its syndrome S is ZERO, i.e., S = rH' = [0 0 ... 0] matrix of order <1 x (n-k)>. If the syndrome S of the received vector <r> is not equal to ZERO, then the received vector <r> contains error.

data.name: label14.Text
data.value: To correct the error, first Syndrome <S> of vector <r> is calculated. S = rH'. Then, from the STANDARD ARRAY the error pattern coset leader having the same syndrome S as that of the received vector <r> is found, i.e., S = rH' = eH' The corrected codeword is obtained using U = r + e.

data.name: summaryTextBox.Text
data.value:
-----> An (n,k) binary linear block code generates a block of 'n' coded bits called codeword symbols from 'k' bits of information called message using a generator matrix . -----> There are 2^n possible values for 'n' bits. We select 2^k values from these 2^n possibilities to form the codeword , such that each message is uniquely mapped to one of these 2^k codewords. If this mapping is linear then the block code is called a linear block code. -----> All Matrices:- One Message = < m1 m2 ... mk > [ 1 x k ] Generator = < v11 v12 ... v1n > [ k x n ] < v21 v22 ... v2n > < ... ... ... ... > < vk1 vk2 ... vkn > One Codeword = [ 1 x n ] = < m1 m2 ... mk > < v11 v12 ... v1n > < v21 v22 ... v2n > < ... ... ... ... > < vk1 vk2 ... vkn > * There are (2^k) messages => (2^k) codewords . Generator = [ P | Ik ] (Systematic Form) [ k x n ] Parity Matrix

= < p11 p12 ... p1(n-k) > [ k x (n-k) ] < p21 p22 ... p2(n-k) > < ... ... ... ... > < pk1 pk2 ... pk(n-k) > Identity = < 1 0 ... 0 > [ k x k ] < 0 1 ... 0 > < ... ... ... > < 0 0 ... 1 > Parity Check = [ I(n-k) | P' ] [ (n-k) x n ] * Matrix P' [ (n-k) x k ] is TRANSPOSE of the parity matrix P. * Matrix H' [ n x (n-k) ] is TRANSPOSE of the parity check matrix H. Received Vector = < r1 r2 ... rn > [ 1 x n ] Syndrome of r, = rH' [ 1 x (n-k) ] One Error Pattern = < e1 e2 ... en > [ 1 x n ] Syndrome of e, = eH' [ 1 x (n-k) ] * There are [ (2^n) - 1 ] different ERROR Patterns including, ---- n^C_1 or 'n' -> 1-bit error patterns. ---- n^C_2 2-bit error patterns. ---- n^C_3 3-bit error patterns. ---- n^C_4 4-bit error patterns. ............................................................................ ---- n^C_n or 1 -> n-bit error pattern. *Standard Array is a [ 2^(n-k) x (2^k) ] marix with [2^(n-k) - 1] error patterns only. -----> The rate of the code is Rc = k/n information bits per codeword symbol . If the codeword symbols are transmitted across the channel at a rate of Rs symbols/second, then the information rate associated with an (n, k) block code is Rb = Rc * Rs = kn Rs bits/second. Thus we see that block coding reduces the data rate compared to what we obtain with uncoded modulation by the code rate Rc. -----> Group codes are a special kind of block codes. They comprise a set of codewords, U1 U2 … UN, which contain the "all zeros" codeword (e.g. 00000) and exhibit a special property called closure. This property means that if any two valid codewords are subject to a bit wise EX - OR operation then they will produce another valid codeword in the set.
